In [9]:
# Imputing NaN values with the mean of each column
X_train_numeric = X_train[numerical_features].fillna(X_train[numerical_features].mean())
X_test_numeric = X_test[numerical_features].fillna(X_test[numerical_features].mean())  # Same for test set
In [10]:
#Scaling the dataset

X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test_numeric)

In [21]:
# Plotting ROC Curve and AUC
fpr_train, tpr_train, thresholds_train = roc_curve(y_train, y_pred_train_binary)
fpr_test, tpr_test, thresholds_test = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_test_binary)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

# Plotting the ROC curve
plt.plot(fpr_train, tpr_train, color='blue', label=f'Train ROC curve (AUC = {auc_train:.2f})')
plt.plot(fpr_test, tpr_test, color='red', label=f'Test ROC curve (AUC = {auc_test:.2f})')

# Plotting the diagonal line (random model) AUC = 0.5
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='gray', linestyle='--')

# Adding titles and labels
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('ROC Curve with AUC')

# Add legend to plot
plt.legend(loc='lower right')

# Display the plot
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

The accuracy is not good. So, we need tuning more

In [ ]:
# Choosing an instance from the test set to explain
i = 9

# Defining a custom predict function that returns probabilities
def predict_fn(X):

    decision_function_values = one_class_svm.decision_function(X)

    return np.column_stack([1 - (decision_function_values > 0), (decision_function_values > 0)])

explanation = explainer.explain_instance(X_test[i], predict_fn, num_features=5)
explanation.show_in_notebook()

The business parking garage and business parking stree are the most influential feature for parking validation
